{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500856"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1689"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1689"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.11,0.78,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51011"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1614"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43092"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51011"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old carpenter presents to large metropolitan Emergency Department with a two-day history of rapid onset of low back pain. This came on after lifting some heavy packages at work. This back pain is associated with pain radiating down the outer aspect of his left leg. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, there is tenderness over the L5/S1 region. He is unable to do a straight leg raise to 20 degrees with onset of pain. Ankle jerk reflex is absent on the left side and normal on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain X-ray of lumbar spine","Ultrasound lumbar spine","CT spine","MRI spine","CT myelography"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history of acute lower back pain radiating down one leg with focal tenderness over L5/S1, in combination with impaired leg raise test and absent ankle jerks is highly suggestive of a disc prolapse, mostly likely at L5/S1 disc (ankle jerk is S1 nerve). \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine \u003C/strong\u003Eis the imaging modality of choice for disc prolapses as it visualises soft tissue well, and does not use ionising radiation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scans\u003C/strong\u003E are also used for soft tissue, but they use ionising radiation and hence are not the first choice of investigation when an MRI is available. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT myelography\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to visualise disc prolapses, however it requires intrathecal injection of contrast followed by either CT or X-ray of the spine. Its accuracy is comparable to MRI and latest generation CT, but it is practically more involved and unnecessary for this patient. CT myelography has become rare with the increased availability of MRI and latest generation CT scanners. A CT myelogram would be used for disc protrusion if MRI was contraindicated and metal is causing artifact on the CT. It is also used for identification of a CSF leak.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain X-ray of the lumbar spine\u003C/strong\u003E can be a good way to visualise bony pathologies that may cause lower back pain, such as crush fractures. In the community setting, this may be the most appropriate investigation as it is cheap and readily available, however it is not going to give any visualisation of soft tissue structures such as intervertebral discs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not used for imaging of a suspected disc prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MRI is the imaging modality of choice for lumbar disc prolapse"],"references":["Kim JH, van Rijn RM, van Tulder MW, Koes BW, de Boer MR, Ginai AZ, et al. Diagnostic accuracy of diagnostic imaging for lumbar disc herniation in adults with low back pain or sciatica is unknown; a systematic review. Chiropr Man Therap. 2018;26:37. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6102824/","Kamei K, Hanai K, Matsui N. Ultrasonic level diagnosis of lumbar disc herniation. Spine (Phila Pa 1976). 1990;15(11):1170-4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2267613/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36255"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-20T08:36:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-20T08:37:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1689"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51011"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","